The answer to the question depends on what is "herd immunity". According to Wikipedia, "herd immunity" is "an indirect form of immunization in which a population becomes immune due to a high percentage of individuals being immune to a disease". In other words, herd immunity occurs when a high percentage of a population has become immune to a disease, thereby protecting the vulnerable population from getting the disease.

Israel has not achieved herd immunity because, as I previously stated, only 56% of the population is fully vaccinated. According to the CDC, "herd immunity requires about 93.3% vaccination coverage". Therefore, because only 56% of the population is vaccinated, and because herd immunity requires 93.3% vaccination coverage, Israel has not yet achieved herd immunity.
